defaultIntroduction:default&#xa0;
defaultEating Better: for a fair, green, healthy future
default is a
default 
defaultUK alliance 
defaultthat is 
defaultraising awareness of the need
default for food policies that put sustainable 
defaultfood 
defaultconsumption at the heart of 
defaultsolutions to national and global food security challenges.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe are calling for action by governments, the food industry and all those who can make a difference to help people move towards eating less meat and more food that’s better for us and the planet, a
defaults part of the vital task of creating sustainable food and farming systems.
default&#xa0;
defaultLaunched in July 2013 with the endorsement of
default 
defaultHugh 
defaultFearnley-Whittingstall
default, Eating 
defaultBetter’s
default growing support includes 
default36
default national 
defaultorganisations
default and partner networks
default spanning the brea
defaultdth of health, environment, social justice, animal welfare, international development, resource use, sustainable business and faith perspectives.
default (see Appendix 1)
default&#xa0;
defaultEating Better encourages a culture where we place greater value on the food we eat, the anim
defaultals that provide it and the people who produce it.
default&#xa0;
default Eating Better supports farmers who produce meat in a sustainable way.
default 
defaultEating Better has called for a global conversation about meat consumption
default,
default which has as its goal a world in which everyone values and
default has access to healthy, humane and sustainable diets.
default&#xa0;
default High meat consuming countries and individuals have reduced their consumption in line with health recommendations and greenhouse gas reduction targets.
default&#xa0;
default Meat is produced humanely and sustainably, its pr
defaultoduction provides sustainable livelihoods, environmental benefits and it is consumed in quantities consistent with good health and global resource use capacity.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe welcome the 
defaultEnvironment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs 
defaultCommittee
default’s Inquiry into food security
default.
default 
default 
defaultOur submission has 
defaultbeen prepared in consultation with our supporting 
defaultorg
defaultanisations
default and partner networks.  
default&#xa0;
defaultOur response
default addresses
default Q1: How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including u
defaultsing resources more efficiently and Q7: 
defaultWays of increasing self
default sufficiency in products for which the UK has a comparative advantage
default.
